<text id="TwaRedpT">

<body>
<head>MT Letter to James Redpath<lb>
Elmira, 20 April 1872</head>

<div1 type="letter">
<opener> 
<seg>
<figure entity="TwaR001">
</figure>
</seg>
<dateline> 
<date n="20 April">Elmira, Apl. 20.</date>
</dateline>
<salute>Dear Red --</salute>
</opener>

<p>Warrington's article was delicious.  <hi rend="underline">I</hi> want to go for Timothy one of these days -- & shall.</p><lb>

<p>Our tribe are flourishing -- the new cub most of all.  I was very sorry to hear such sad news of Fall's family, & sincerely hope the calamity will proceed no farther.</p><lb>

<p>I hope to see you all when I come up to the Jubilee. -- </p>

<p>
<figure entity="TwaR002">
</figure>
</p>
<p>a little solo in hopes of getting a chance to sing there.</p><lb>

<p>Could you jam this item into the Advertiser?  I hate to see our fine success wholly uncelebrated:
<q>Mark Twain's new book, "Roughing It" has sold 43,000 copies in two months & a half.  Only 17,000 copies of "The Innocents Abroad" were sold in the first two & a half months.</q></p>

<p>I order a copy to be sent to you a couple of weeks ago.  If it has</p>
</div1>
</body>
</text>
